	<table width="85%" cellspacing="3" cellpadding="0" border="0" align="center">
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Author:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>Dwedit</b> [ Sat Dec 22, 2012 12:00 pm ]</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Post subject:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>Re: Tiny Windows XP utlity that gives Aero Snap feature</b></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />I haven't tested my program with dual monitors, but I wrote it with dual monitors in mind.  It's supposed to pick the monitor that the active window has the most area covering, and snaps it to that screen.  So if the Win32 API functions work like they should, everything should be fine on dual monitors.<br /><br />As for Windows 7's real Aero Snap feature, it's very nice.  You can also drag a window to the extreme left and extreme right side of the screen, and it will make the window cover the left or right half of the screen.  When you do this, the mouse cursor must touch the edge of the screen.  So getting the window's left edge to the left edge of the screen doesn't matter, the mouse cursor needs to be there for the feature to trigger.  Windows 7 also shows a preview of where the window will be placed.<br />My program doesn't support snapping windows on the screen when dragging them, it only supports the WindowsKey + Left/Right shortcut key.  Which is still damn useful.<br />I don't think the Window 7 Aero Snap feature requires Aero to be enabled, but you can see if the built-in snap feature still works with Aero disabled.  If it doesn't work, use my program.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


